A struggle pushed at the extreme: MP3 players against mobiles.
You will be advised, how to choose
While virtually every mobile can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can phone.
It seems clear that it is better to buy only one phone.
It does not prevent sufficient reasons for obtaining an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the house a high-end expensive gramophone to put the new album of Maxim Turbulenc.
On the one hand, such musical products do not go on vinyl discs, and, from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
Now, if there's in your shelves of loaded vinyl discs, with rock art, jazz or blues, you're probably dreaming at least of such a gramophone.
The same is true of music during travel, namely compressed music, to be described in a simplified way - of music in MP3.
Here too, there are categories based on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns for a reader, in the same way that a Pink Floyd fan would have a hard time supporting listeners bought for twenty crowns in the market.
These are two extremes, among which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
Battery life is also decisive
Some high-end music readers are capable of much more than simply reading music, but these are unknown functions, of course, most of the furniture.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the first functions, phone calls and SMS sending, it is able to read music and movies, record them, it has a variable quality camera and can, for example, serve as a navigational device.
And if you take into account smartphones and communicators, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no refrigerator knows how to grill meat and no television will take photographs, we are almost witnessing a miracle.
However, the universal character of the mobile is not without inconvenience.
