If, in addition, you can call from time to time, look up, to be sure, a second recharge for work - this being valid even for cheaper devices.
The problem will not arise for MP3 players, who are capable, as a result of a reload, of continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the least performing ones.
Another problem arises when recording music in the mobile.
Unfortunately, a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially not all of them can be directly connected to the computer, without special software.
Of course, you can record music directly on the memory card, but few card readers know to take it without reduction, given the tiny dimensions of the memory cards used in the mobiles.
With regard to readers, you do not need, except for (iPod), any software.
Just fill the music device from the computer through the USB connector.
Most mobiles and readers will create themselves a media library classified according to the name of the interpreter, the title of the album, the style, or then the judgment of the user.
Some devices display only an index with a tree structure, in the way of Windows Exploration, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Readers are easier to manipulate, mobiles have more know-how
In choosing a specific device, be especially interested in the lifespan of the accumulator, in the capacity of memory, in the quality and type of output of sound and, of course, in the ease of order.
If the music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if in the day you will listen to it for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you just have any mobile reading MP3.
Practically all the furniture is now capable of it.
You don't even have to pay too much attention to music formats that the mobile or player is able to read.
All come to read the MP3s and the vast majority of the music that will reach you will just have this format.
It is one of the most common formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices also read WMA-format music.
The AAC (format used by the Apple firm and its iPods), as far as it is concerned, is less common.
High-end furniture also enables, for example, the purchase of online music.
Simply visit the operator's web pages (or other supplier's) from the mobile phone and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a convincing reason to obtain a musical mobile.
The operator's offer is unfortunately miserable and, in most cases, it is limited to radio tubes quickly made.
