A first virtual operator will win Chechnya this same year.
Maybe
The mobile market in Czechia is relatively advanced, our operators offering almost the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force conventional operators to lower prices.
Maybe he won't be missing for long.
We have mentioned, on many occasions, on Mobil.cz, the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The ČTú (The Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of an SMS was higher in us than in the rest of the Union, confirmed it.
This is how, following the last steps of the European Commission in the area of roaming fee regulation, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be for some customers of Czech mobile operators less expensive than in the country.
How is it possible for Czech prices to remain so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really like to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that goes far beyond 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvořák, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTú), who stated several times that there was no place in Czechia for another operator, is chorus with the operators.
It is probably true that a classic operator with his own network seems to have no more chances (in fact, now, he would find only difficult frequencies).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that resulted in a considerable drop in prices, which would then also have to react to conventional operators.
However, even before the entry of the fiestas such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the market, voices similar to what we hear today at home were heard in Britain.
However, it appeared that there was still room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We are not obliged to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch, in Poland, of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, the operator managed to win over 100 thousand customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
Let's add that behind the Mobilking, there is the Penta Financial Group, which has among other things the U:fon in Czechia.
The advantage of virtual operators being the possibility to focus on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be effective, they need much less customers than a conventional operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the relatively high construction, operation and maintenance costs of the mobile network.
This is how virtual operators in the world look like low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers, in Britain, text messages at least twice as expensive as its competitors.
But, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, placing on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
"The real men choose Mobilking - an operator that pleases them and they can trust," said David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, exploiting this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be likely to work with us as well.
Miroslav Čepický, Vodafone spokesperson, in doubt: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
The greater the fact that he is relatively saturated from the point of view of the supply of services."
In Czechia, no chance, tell mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be a virtual operator in Czechia, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in Czechia negotiations are not very encouraging.
The launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries in our area," said in a telephone entertainment for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group.
It therefore indirectly confirmed that the operators in Czechia were not, in any case, in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible so that a potential competitor cannot appear.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the business customer field, has not, for quite a long time, been hiding its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We tend to be able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner it's gonna be the better.
We have already held negotiations on this possibility on several occasions with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have succeeded in moving forward in the negotiations," says Pavel Kaidl's spokesman.
The future is therefore perhaps promising.
According to informal information, it seems that we could perhaps host the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for now, its creation is accompanied by a total silence.
"At the moment, we do not think that there is any place on the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is compared with other very specific ones.
At the moment, no subject with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," said Vladimil Sršeň of the press department of Telefonika O2, in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also relate to the specificity of the Czech market.
The spokesperson for T-Mobilea Martina Kemrová states in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "We have not registered for the moment a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a basis."
And she adds: "It is practically excluded that a virtual operator appears in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited time period, we should now have a concrete agreement."
Vodafone instead directs its attention to the fulfilment of requests to obtain its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický said in relation to this: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
This is what we believe means most customer input.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to establish a common network for a fast mobile internet."
The responsible authorities: in phase with the operators
The mobile operators' approach is easily understandable, another operator's entry would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and thus to a decrease in their profit.
What, then, is it good to facilitate the arrival of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, the operators know how to hear themselves as a slot thief. Chicane accompanies the creation of the U:phone also testifies to it.
The greatest apparent pressure on the ČTÚ, when creating the U:fon, was the one exercised by the T-Mobile company.
This shows information available to the public from the ČTÚ web pages.
But today, the U:fon is willing to serve as an argument not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted in this connection: "Competition on the mobile market has also recently been enhanced by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the character of the mobile market in RT, it is clear that the entry of an additional player would subject it, and above all its services, to high requirements."
But given the attitude of mobile operators here, the indifference of Czech regulators seems disconcerting.
However, this is not just the attitude of the ČTú, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in the economic competition in Czechia.
The latter belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
However, the latter adopts, in the face of this problem, its typical position.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the relevant virtual operator regarding the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached for the time being, since the offer of potential stakeholders has not previously presented sufficient interest to conventional operators," said Kristián Chalupa in response to our question from the UOHS Department of External Relations.
A statement thus made would not surprise the representatives of the operators.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and on the other hand, so that no one takes advantage of his position on the market, such a statement is more than misleading.
Even more than Kristián Chalupa adds: "Out abroad, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a decrease in prices of mobile telephone services."
However, pressure in the sense of a fair functioning of the market and a lower price does not appear to be part of the UOHS interests.
What is really shocking is the almost touching agreement of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, if this is really a coincidence, naturally arises.
In the same way, a price of gasoline strictly identical to all service stations is probably due to the chance and the hard fight of competition.
"The Office has not noted, in this regard, signs of anticompetitive behaviour, so it has no reason to intervene in one way or another.
None of the operators has a dominant position, so none of them has an increased responsibility for their behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably missing even the telecom regulator," he stated in his statement Chaloupa.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTú that telecommunications is, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators have a dominant position on such a market.
However, some legal experts propose another view of things: in order for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, the consent of the network operator must be obtained at each time.
And the mobile operator logically has the monopoly on his network.
This is how he necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of his activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the UOHS that three mobile operators proceed in a similar manner.
However, complaints from many interested parties (including GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Taking responsibility for the ČTÚ is a fairly common turn in communications, by which the UOHS washes its hands of the case.
We have already encountered this kind of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to introduce the recently adopted Telecommunication Act to extend ČTú's powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised to improve the situation.
This requires the UOHS representatives to know very well, but their interests are apparently elsewhere.
When no one looks, it can work.
However, the operation of a kind of virtual pseudooperators, several in Czech mobile networks, remains unclear.
They are companies publishing their own price lists of mobile telephone services, but they are only public in part.
In most cases, it is a matter of firms dealing with multi-level marketing.
For example, specific mobile telephone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms generally come only to the electorate.
The magic tour consists of the fact that the company in front of the operator is a classic business client, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important client, she gets special price offers (and others).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a resale.
"If there were to happen what you are referring to, it could be a violation of the contractual conditions that we would consider and which could lead to a cessation of collaboration with the company in question," answered our question regarding this problem Martina Kemrová.
However, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such activity has not been reached to those responsible for mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, this may be thousands of customers.
However, no operator takes a decision against such a procedure.
In fact, the activities of these firms bring them unfavourable benefits, and at the same time, as opposed to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them at all with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický indicates the possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are only used by a percentage of negligible customers.
In addition, they are obliged to admit that the SIM card on their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the way ordinary customers of mobile operators."
But that is exactly what should seem strange to ČTú.
In addition, another question is raised in the UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes on such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the UOHS has relatively broad powers to be able to reveal such an activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators, who claim that they have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions would prohibit it.
When we will no longer be the most expensive country
As we have mentioned several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has resulted in a considerable decrease in service prices.
However, virtually in all the countries where virtual operators appeared, conventional operators were trying, sometimes more, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small, or even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
It is precisely at this level that the regulatory bodies in the developed countries intervened, which did not defend the interests of mobile operators, but that of their customers.
Both through formal measures and through informal pressure, they eventually obtained the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators are dealing with this issue in the way a hot potato is being disposed of by transmitting it to a near target.
As a result of the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in skills is more than beneficial to them.
But don't throw your sleeve after the cognate.
If the information on the flow is true and a virtual operator will soon appear in our home, the Czech mobile market may be moving.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the UOHS will not be able to remain impermissible in the face of the rejection (to discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the day of Czech nationality, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde kastav m.j (Where is my homeland?).
The hymn was once again recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo song, an interpretation with heart and an instrumental version.
The song is provided by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiaš and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the hymn arrangements.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek sees the Czech national song as one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted Český rozhlas (Czech Public Radio), he chose for the interpretation of solo versions of singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I was trying to take care of what the two singers, as well as the choir, had a good dictionary, so that one could understand the words, which they sing simultaneously," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate, next year, its 175th anniversary.
Kde's song was first resounding in 1834 on the stavovské divadlo boards (the State Theatre) in Fidlovačka (Kermesse des sapvetiers), a Czech piece by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by music by František Škroup.
It has become popular and people have spontaneously appropriated it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first couple naturally became an integral part of the national anthem.
It will remain one of seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
