The Southeasts called for a referendum in the USA
In 1945 the Germans of the South asked that Šumava be integrated into the United States.
This is the result of a letter filed in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (The Scientific Library of the South Bohemian Republic).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, at least we want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of South Germans allegedly addressed the President of the USA with such a desire.
This derives from, among other things, a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
Germans of Český Krumlov in the letter urge the US President not to allow "šumavská župa" (region of forests south of Bohemian) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have fully understood the situation and we want to be absolutely sure that the words proclaim that the American troops come into the German territory not in bullies and enemies, but in liberators," is written in the letter, "People, to whom the fate of Šumava holds hearts."
Given that the rallying in Czechoslovakia is not so promising - by knowing the Czech national character - that of brutality, senseless attitude, misunderstanding, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take into his hands the protection of Šumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe, that you would grant this territory to a foreign State to us, that oppresses and destroys minorities and that has contributed nothing to the Allies' victory without taking into account the opinion of the 4 million inhabitants," is the letter.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of the "Czech Oppressors".
If the President of the USA questioned the Germans' opinion of Šumava, he would only have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to determine whether his inhabitants wanted to be part of the USA, or to live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, given the current knowledge of post-war history, seem somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it well illustrates the expectations of the Germans of the Sudetes of the time.
While the Czech Germans had to at least find out that the question of their expulsion from the Republic would arise, very few of them had such an opportunity.
Some were waiting for the United States and Britain to get a certain kind of autonomy for the Southeast.
Others thought they'd just stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born at České Budějovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as German of České Budějovice, engaged in the Navy in the Baltic countries.
When at the end of the war, he was captured by the English and placed in the catch camp of the Holstein region, dozens of Czech Germans came to see him to teach them the Czech.
"They believed that once they returned home, the Czech would benefit them," Chalupa said.
None of the Germans captured in Czechoslovakia before the war believed that, following the Beneš decrees, he would be expelled from the Republic.
