Rats also have sensations
A rat or a cockroach in the face of danger, does that mean he also feels fear?
Neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced of this: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we verify that he feels the same when he behaves in the same way as we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles of the answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else so far could prove it just as we cannot prove that other human beings have a conscience.
But in this case, at least one can hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the issues of feeling or in general consciousness, we enter difficult terrain because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, he does the same thing as many other animals: he does death, escape or attack.
Human beings behave in the same way, that is why some scientists deduce a comparable subjective experience.
However, I don't believe it.
Two aspects of the structure of the brain make the transposition of our subjective experience to that of the animals difficult.
One aspect is that circuits associated almost always with human consciousness include the prefrontal lateral cortex (because of its participation in short-term memory and management and enforcement functions).
This vast region is much more developed in human beings than in other primates and seems to be completely absent in other beings.
So at least for these aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being differs even from the other primates.
Another significant characteristic could reside in the linguistic nature of Man: a large part of his existence is related to language, which often means that his conscience depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if the conscience was not to depend on the language, it would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, regardless of the way it is produced, would probably differ much from most of our states of conscience.
That is why it is also difficult to determine what the conscience can look like in other animals.
If this, internal and subjective, does not allow itself to be measured or, because of this particular hardware, to analyze on the basis of our own experience, then its observation poses major problems.
Most of my developments refer to the content of the conscious experience, but there is another aspect of the consciousness that should be more easily accessible scientifically.
