"I photograph the master out of the scene to capture elements of his character" Günther Bauer - Photographer
No heels, no woolen clothes.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, released from all tensions to obtain the relaxed appearance of man or woman.
On one side, the artist.
On the other hand, the person.
Inseparable except in intimacy, in these unknown moments of the general public, where one discovers intimate gestures and stolen views of artists who do not care to ride on stage.
German Günther Bauer mixes in "Flamenco - people" the theatre of some performances with singers, dancers and guitarists with this less known side of the artists.
In this project, the photographer resumes the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the programming of the month of Flemish Photography, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, greater every day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" may be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that these are not typical images of artists on stage.
These photographed people "on the street" are artists able to transmit on stage passion, sadness, joy... by captivating the public.
To capture moments of personality from these artists, you don't have to take pictures on stage.
They have a clean personality and character.
What I was interested in was to create an intimate atmosphere that allows me to capture with the camera the moments of personality of the flamenco stars."
With the festival "Chant populaire des Mines", Bauer began a long journey in 1997 to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a photo plated camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of the camera and the material, re-commend the classic photography.
The implementation of various stylistic means breaks with the classical side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day".
It is not about dance or singing in itself, but about the personality and character of the artist who captured the audience with his art.
The search for the essentials and magic has been the constant of this work that is presented these days at the El Fotómata gallery.
Flamenco stars such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about sixty-ten artists.
The project has become an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a collection book of portraits presented at the gallery.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of old sports" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves photographing people's portrait, knowing them and being able to enter their lives for a longer or longer time.
I think in photography the portrait is the most difficult kind.
You find yourself in front of people, characters that sometimes you don't know or that leave you just a few minutes to be able to take a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true."
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco called "Flamenco - people" is presented at the El Fotómata Gallery, located on the 20th Street of the Mata (the road parallel to the People's of Hercules) which will be open until October 16th.
