I do not relate to those who wake up very awake telling us something that happened the day before, but to the children who talk during their sleep.
The first time this happens, it may surprise you, but in reality it doesn't matter.
It's a benign disturbance of sleep that's called sleepwalking.
It is quite common, especially among children and adolescents.
I'm sure there's more than one who talks at night.
This may occur in a very sporadic way (once in life for example associated with a severe fever episode), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance
They are often linked to other sleeping disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, nocturnal emuresis (pipi per bed) or somnambulism, but this is not always the case.
As we have said before, they can also be associated with very severe fevers, stress situations or overexcitement.
In any case, it is a phenomenon that is not studied.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
He may speak with a quiet little voice, with isolated words, murmurs, or on the contrary with screams, cries, long speeches...
In the event that sleepoloquia becomes very common, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check if there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety and in order to get an explanation for this problem.
We said that this is a benign alteration, which is why there is no treatment, except if it is related to another disturbance in sleep that can be taken care of (e.g., if it is related to sleep apnea or stress).
What we can do is take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to sleep.
Therefore, seek calm games and avoid programs or television series that are more or less violent.
With very nervous children who have trouble relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm inside.
This will allow the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as the dreams appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless for the child and that the next day he will not remember what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him.
It's useless because he's unconscious and you'd wake him up.
Even if he speaks, he sleeps and so rests.
Remember that if he gets very anxious several times, it is advisable to consult a doctor or check what causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not usual), do not be tempted to ask him for information.
You won't get anything, because he's asleep, he's not aware of how to organize his thinking.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you will not know what he is dreaming about, of the thought of how you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw from it.
Never tell the child that you can question him during the night to know his secrets.
Not even kidding.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's an episode that only takes a few minutes.
