Before flying for the United States, Nicolas Sarkozy is going to make a hijack by Brittany.
In the face of the demonstration of force of fishermen who have greatly disturbed the access of several Breton and Norman ports on Monday, the President of the Republic decided to visit the port of Guilvinac, in the Finistère, on Tuesday morning to meet their representatives.
They promised to welcome him "in a constructive spirit" and hope that he would "come with concrete proposals".
A presidential visit that falls at the same time as a general assembly of the "crisis committee" created by Breton fishermen to obtain measures in the face of oil prices, which reached a record of more than 1.14 euros per litre on average.
According to Elysée David Martinon's spokesman, the president "will discuss with them solutions that can be imagined to help their companies regain competitiveness and to secure the conditions of employment and remuneration of the sailors."
