The sailors have already demonstrated on Monday their determination by burning from dawn tires and pallets in front of the fuel deposits of the ports of Brest, and Lorient, while demonstrations took place in Concarneau or Saint-Brieuc.
The movement spread to other ports of the Atlantic façade and the Manche, as well as to the Sables of Olonne, in Vendée, where the trawlers stayed on dock, or to the Havre, where some twenty ships blocked the movements of the merchant ships.
The fishermen of La Turballe and the Croisic, in Loire-Atlantique, stopped in the evening the blockade of the important Donges refinery.
Those of Boulogne-sur-Mer decided to wait for the Wednesday meeting to be held in the department to decide on possible actions.
In Guilvinec, the "crisis committee" must decide on Tuesday about the follow-up to the movement and participation in the planned interview with the Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries in Paris.
But some Breton fishermen do not want to be represented by those responsible for the National Fisheries Committee, who did not support their movement.
"The strike will continue" because "the fishermen will not let go" and "do not want to move to Paris", for example, said Liliane Cariou, chairman of the Lorient Fisheries Committee.
