Interview - Red blood safe
Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday the 10th anniversary of his foundation, and his president, Dr. Francine Décary, had reason to rejoice because Hema-Québec became one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
And above all, he restored the public's confidence that had been seriously undermined by the blood scandal contaminated in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and public grunt, in February 1994, the Government of Canada instituted a public investigation, chaired by Justice Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations for such disaster to stop happening.
While Judge Krever was late in filing his report, some provinces then set up a committee to plan for a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee has completed this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Hema-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to provide all other provinces and territories.
"In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, almost 38 per cent of people still trusted in the blood system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
In an effort to improve the safety of blood and work products in the field during the years that followed, we regained public confidence," she said before proudly affirming that in early 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population now trusted Hema-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary keeps in mind that "confidence is something extremely fragile."
Hema-Québec applied the precautionary principle from its establishment on 28 September 1998.
At that time, many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, were being dealt with in Europe.
"And we did not know at all whether this disease could be transmitted by blood.
It was then based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports that when it is not known and a serious disease may arise, in the case of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a brain degeneration that inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are introduced.
In April 1999, therefore, the blood of those who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980 was denied.
A few years ago, however, it was shown beyond doubt that this disease was transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle applied had meaning."
In 1999 a much more sensitive technique for HIV testing appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (TAN) that enable the presence of the virus itself to be detected directly in the blood of donors and not in anti-virus antibodies, on which the tests used until then were based.
The NTAs have been able to shorten the silent period, which extends between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This period could be reduced to less than one week.
Thus, the risk of some donors being infected was substantially reduced without the knowledge and could not be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of getting HIV-contaminated blood.
"In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will need to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of transmission of HIV occurs by a blood product.
I believe that today we can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health," says the head of the management of Hema-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the security of our products.
We never know what pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We need to be constantly vigilant," continued Dr. Décary before pointing out that in addition to a secure supply, Hema-Québec must also provide adequate supplies.
"Needs increase because the population grows older.
As anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often require red blood cell or platelet recharge.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the network of blood donors, which is an average of only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation."
Every person in health, aged 18 and older who meets the eligibility criteria, however, can give blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of those who propose their blood are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a country where malaria is prevalent, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3%, we are able to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
The shortages are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this donor network as they age and can no longer give their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Today's life is so scary, we rarely find the time to spend an hour giving his blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec provides not only blood products but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eye globes and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec which also manages the only public blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord once considered to be a biomedical waste is a blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukaemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the banking of our thousandth blood sample of cordon and it is expected to take more than a thousand a year.
We should start proposing this for grafts early next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this cordon blood sampling program as very popular.
"Mothers are disappointed they can't have access to it," because Hema-Québec has no means to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
