Following an Orwellian logic, he claims that the world's largest goldsmith company has attempted a defamation of six million against three authors and a small publishing house without the envelope in order to launch a "transparent public debate".
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of prosecution in defamation, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely hidden by Mr. Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to lead to the ruin of anyone who dares to support a stand against his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and the editor of the Black Canada book will have to spend considerable amounts in order to prepare their defense and to fight, to very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the miner.
Tactical, in these unequal struggles, is, in fact, often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a regulation on the friendly who will banish the opposition in addition to oppressing anyone who will dare to look again at the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was in front of the public that she should have presented her vision of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, discussions in Canada are usually done with the exchange of ideas rather than with matriculation.
It was therefore sufficient to open its books, records and to establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust public opinion and reject requests and letters of support from black Canada authors from the back.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he could at the same time ask for a "public" debate while disregarding the views of that same audience?
In the Vice-President's world, it seems that this word refers only to fat lawyers paid, not all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In democracy, even detractors have the right to speak.
What you don't understand - or don't want to understand - Barrick Gold is that the public who supports black Canada's authors and publishers is doing it first because it rejects the brutal way of mining.
This audience is prepared to hear Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not in the context of what many perceive as a prosecution-boat (following the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just placed a standstill at the authors of Black Canada urging them to stop using this term...).
Beyond Mr. Garver's surreal speech, Barrick Gold's continuation is a direct attack on freedom of university research and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, in block, the right to quote credible sources and to debate on facts and interpretations, which are the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss topics that appeal to rich companies in this world in a country such as Canada, subject to prosecution, who can do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following the scientific standards used by black Canada authors.
She has a right to reply.
The academic community we belong to has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's move clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the academic world, as well as for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms that limit this kind of abusive prosecution.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Hear · Global Voices
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the biggest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the US$700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has plagued Wall Street for months still needs to be endorsed by the two Houses of Congress.
It provides for, inter alia, better control by the electors of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for non-payment, as well as a right to look at wages paid to the executives of the rescue companies.
Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, President of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday after a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done in a way that has opened up the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street," the democrat explained.
"This is the fundamental point: if we do not do so, the trauma, chaos and disturbances on the American daily life will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had turned on the spree in the last few hours, fearing the effect that would result in a new failure on the mood of investors.
The deadline was the opening of the markets this morning.
Lately associated with the negotiations, the two candidates for the U.S. presidential election were rather in favour of the agreement, however, without failing to express their discontent that it is necessary to reach that end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has attributed the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, including that of allowing owners to keep their homes and that of the government-responsible business leaders.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to be welcomed.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on the American television waves.
Asked about another channel to see whether he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, said, "I would like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The big lines that I read [show] is something that we're all going to have to digest and with which we're going to be able to move forward.
The choice to do nothing is simply not acceptable," he said.
The 700 billion plan aims to buy with taxpayers' money the dubious, risky and invincible debts of the US financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the outbreak of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of mortgages at risk (subprimary) before extending to other more widespread forms of credit securities (CPAA) and leading to a liquidity freeze and the detonation of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republicans who had led to the first draft of an agreement last week.
It is believed to have come out of this impasse since Democrats have accepted that certain "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only secured by the government rather than purchased.
In order to round up the angles for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added that if the government was to make losses for five years with this program, it could introduce new taxes to help it recover its release.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first instalment of 250 billion to which another 100 billion may be added if the President judges it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion should be endorsed by another vote of the Congress.
In exchange for his assistance, Washington will be able to obtain participations in the rescue companies that will pay him dividends in case of profit and that he will be able to resell when the storm passes.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay seizure procedures for housing for the real estate loans involved in this plan, as well as to set limits on the remuneration and start-up allowances paid to the managers of the companies concerned.
The architects of the plan would like him to be put to the vote of the House of Representatives today, and of the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plans will have green fire.
In fact, voices continued to rise yesterday against this project, both in the Republican and Democratic camp.
"Of course, Washington does not hear you," said Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House's Finance Committee, at his electorate.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one to take advantage of taxpayers."
Animator of a small group at the Congress called "the caucus of skeptics", Democratic representative Brad Sherman presented things differently, but reached the same conclusion.
"Four hundred eminent economic teachers, including three Nobel Prizes, wrote to us to say: we ask Congress not to hurry and carefully examine the way to be taken," he said yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again evidence of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US).
The intervention by the Governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg was made necessary after the BNP Paribas Bank announced that it had renounced its acquisition of its competitor in full shipwreck since it lost 2 billion euros (US 2.9%) in the U.S. venture capital lending crisis.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and ten largest insurers.
"This is not lost money," said the Dutch Minister of Finance, Wouter Bos.
In exchange, a right to vote in the bank and influence is recovered.
It's just something that savers and households now appreciate the uncertain announcement of times."
Meanwhile, on the other hand, the British government seemed to be in the process of nationalizing another bank under the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would return all outstanding loans to the Bradford and Bringley Bank, of which more than $41.5 billion (US75.5 billion) of real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would be the one who would buy the branches and customer accounts of the UK bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
