Over-the-counter psychology: why do we spend more money?
In auction sales, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate merchandise.
Neurology and Economics researchers at the University of New York have succeeded in updating the neurological and economic bases of this known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be distanced during this type of competition, such as a auction sale on eBay, and that is why they prefer to even pay a high price.
These researches attempted to develop a neurological pattern of this type of "game" using sales at experimental auctions.
One of the volunteer groups played the loto, while the other group participated in a sale at playful auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance process (RMF), researchers analyzed the active brain areas of experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction sale, a key element of which is the oversales of a third, the whole under the brain trunk, called stritum, was moving intensively during the loss of the party.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-stimulation" of the nervous system.
This is why researchers believe that price rises are due to the leak in the face of the violent reaction of the stratum.
In support of their theories, economic members of this group of researchers continued financial surveillance analyses.
In these cases, three groups surpassed a partner under various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and they did so.
In another group, they promised that if, in addition, they would get out of the game, then they would receive an additional $15 in reward.
While the third group received these $15 before the auction, the group also lost this money, in the event of their loss of the auction.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the emphasis was placed on one victory, while on the other, on the failure.
By proving the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the player team "against failure" were willing to take higher steps than those performed by the control group and the "to victory" group.
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
In fact, each of them explained the phenomena found during auction sales only by the pleasure of winning and the parade at risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped eliminate the contradiction between the two theories, leading, now, to a third explanation." - found Andrew Schotter, the professor of the Faculty of Economic Sciences of the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should we consult a doctor?
Worldwide, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, the chronic liver disease is mentioned as one of the first causes of death.
Patients with hepatitis virus in Hungary are estimated to be 100 miles away, but only seven miles after treatment. This is because the patients often do not know that they are carriers of the virus.
Hepatitis is a generic name given to liver-related infections caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. The inflammation of the liver and yellowishness are characteristic, but pathogens and diseases generated differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogens, are propagated primarily in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tube (e.g. food or contaminated water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses by blood and organic liquids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, vaccination against A and B viruses is also recommended. There is no vaccine against C.
Hepatitis A symptoms occur two to three weeks after the consumption of contaminated foods, generally accompanied by a poor general condition, weakness, stomach and nausea.
Then it develops on the skin and on the white of the eye a visible yellowish, the seals become clearer and the urine takes a darker color. Healing can take two to three weeks.
Around the world, every year, one million people die of the most serious form of this disease, such as cancer or liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that, according to estimates, only one in ten patients receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know how to get to the virus, because pathogen destroys the liver cells in a subtle way. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with C-type chronic hepatitis worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your doctor treating from the observation of symptoms of unknown origin.
The disease can be cured if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, thus the risk of infection disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
On 30 September is the World Day of Hepatitis, organized for the first time in 2004 by the organizations representing the sick around the world.
Its objective is to draw attention to the chronic liver cirrhosis caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does he who grows in God feel less pain?
According to the results of a recent research, religious belief would function as a kind of analgesic, which would have already contributed to making the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British daily Telegraph published an article in which researchers at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experience by analyzing how much belief in God could influence tolerance to the pain of the human being.
As part of this experience for the least bizarre, 12 Catholic believers and so many atheists were subjected to electrochocs, while each of them observed a painting representing the Virgin Mary.
The results show that Catholic believers have been able to exclude much of the suffering.
Thanks to a technique of palpation of the human brain, it was also found that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for pain regulation.
This analysis is the first of a series of experiences, in which academics, scholars, philosophers and theologians participate from different sectors of the university.
More specifically, the experience takes place in the following way: an instrument emitting sparks and disseminating electrochocs is fixed on the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants to look at two paintings in a sustained way, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady with hermine painted by Leonard de Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers at the origin of this experience hoped that the vision of the Virgin Mary evoked a kind of state of faith among believers, while the choice of the painting of Da Vinci, not very different from the first, was about its soothing effect.
Experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during this time, they received 20 electrochocs in four successive parts, while watching either the religious theme painting, or the more general theme.
The Catholics said that, in the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt like "safe" as someone to whom we "care" and they "sustained, and peace invaded them."
In view of the painting of religious themes, they reported 12% pain less than when they looked at Leonard's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself has taken part in the experience, thinks that the same effects can be achieved with any other strong image, in the atheists, provided you find the appropriate photo.
"We should find an image in front of which they react very positively, such as a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
Tom Wright, Bishop of England, welcomed the results of this research.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases change our personality," Wright added.
After these excellent results, there is only the question of what would be the effect on the regulation of the pain of subjects if a Madone painted by Leonard or a painter of the same caliber were shown to believers?
Would the view of a higher quality Virgin Mary lead to better results?
