The intelligent car imitate the bourdon's flight
What would be the best way to develop technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle if it was not the imitation of an existing obstacle detector in nature?
For example, bees.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC, which took place in Japan, bourdonning bees gave the strategic idea of departure to Nissan engineers, to inspire them on how they must design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired self-robotted, BR23C-type system, which he has equipped with bees qualities, the ultimate objective being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee is its own space, of oval shape, which actually resembles much of our safe protection shell - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhiro Doi, the director of the research and development department and the technological public relations of the brand.
The bee's face-eye plays a vital role, as it is able to see in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To imitate the functions of the face-to-face eye, the engineers approached the idea of the laser telemeter.
It identifies obstacles in a 180-degree angle and at a distance of 2 metres in front of the BR23C, it assesses distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which turns it into avoidance maneuver immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it from an angle sufficient to avoid the collision.
Contrary to any existing system, this avoidance manoeuvre is carried out in an instinctive manner.
"If it wasn't so, the mini robot couldn't react fast enough to avoid the obstacle," says Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantly, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and internal layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for now the collision is considered inevitable.
This whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must be carried out in a blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that the bees possess to avoid other bees, in our case, only the rotating movement, acceleration and slowing as maneuvers made available to the mini auto robot could be used.
BR23C uses polymer lithium batteries that are lighter and whose energy concentrate is larger, making their life longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the intelligent instinctive reaction that is paramount, not data processing, and even less the ability to store.
This mechanism should handle only a few incoming signals per second, and respond to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilo-bytes of memory continuously.
There is no need for memory of a giga-byte capacity, or even mega-bytes.
This is the first step towards designing an instant avoidance technology. According to Nissan's estimates, this system will enter the serially manufactured cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver towards his destination by avoiding obstacles on his way.
