Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 - the Central Statistical Office of Hungary is informed.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, while compared to those of a previous year, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of internal price fluctuations and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 3.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
Internal industrial sales prices have only increased to a lesser extent: 0.1 per cent, compared to the previous month.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industry have only increased by 0.1% compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 percent), with first, the manufacture of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 percent, then the production of shoes with 2.5 percent monthly increase.
The higher prices of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the manufacturing sector of chemicals and products (1.6 per cent).
This resulted in deflation in the oil processing sectors (1.4 per cent), the manufacture of machinery and electrical equipment (0.9 per cent), as well as a minimum increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing activities have not changed.
Other sectors of the processing industry increased from 0.2 per cent to 0.9 per cent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, representing a significant weight in the national industrial operation, prices increased by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in the gas price established by the authorities since 1 July.
In a twelve-month comparison, taking into account the domestic sales of the processing sectors, the oil processing sector prices were the most significant increase (32.4%).
In the metallurgical manufacturing sector, there was an increase in prices of 13.2 per cent, while in the important area of food, drink and tobacco production, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price reductions have occurred in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacturing of machinery and electrical equipment (0.3 per cent).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, the price increase has increased between 0.6 percent and 9.1 percent.
Overall, prices increased by 10.2 per cent in the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded 18.7 per cent in the previous year.
Among the domestic trade groups and according to sector allocations, in August, the investment profit-initiating sectors showed the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and material-producing sectors for subsequent processing did not experience any change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase in energy and material production sectors for subsequent processing was observed (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, an inflation of 6.8 per cent was measured, while in the profit-initiating sectors, a decrease of 1.4 per cent was measured.
Export sales prices for the industrial sector in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, while they fell by 3.9 per cent in 12 months.
In one month, our national payment rate decreased by 1.7 per cent compared to the euro, and 7.1 per cent compared to the dollar. Compared to the month of August 2007, it increased by 7.5 per cent against the euro and 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
