Mp3 reader pointed to the finger, they put the hearing at risk.
Listening to music in full volume for a prolonged period using portable musical devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent injuries to the hearing.
This is what the European Commission announces, which, in a press release in Brussels, cites the opinion of the Scientific Committee, on the unexpected and recently identified health risks (Cssseri) of the EU, published today.
"of this scientific report- let's read in the note that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to full-volume music using portable musical devices, for more than an hour per day and a week, are at risk of permanent loss of hearing ability."
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable musical devices and mobile phones in full volume can unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably," says Meglena Kuneva.
"According to scientific data, the EU is responsible for a clear risk and we need to react quickly.
What counts most is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We must also review existing systems of control in the light of scientific opinion, so that they are fully effective and can follow new technologies."
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise generated by them.
"Scientists-concluded the executive Ue- confirm that there are good reasons to be concerned, and that the European Commission will now examine with the Member States and other interested parties what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable music and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical devices to 100Db, but there is increased concern about hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
It is possible to limit these data using solutions such as reduction of levels and length of exposure to noise.
The Scientific Committee Ue notes that users of portable music, who listen to full-volume music (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours per week, are above the current limits on the maximum noise level agreed at the workplace.
Those who listen to music under such conditions for extended periods are at risk of permanent loss of hearing capacity after 5 years.
This is of interest to 5-10% of the users of these devices, and their numbers can be quantified for about 2.5 million and 10 million people in the U.S.
