However, what has just been mentioned is just an example of the changes, of the major changes that the current economic earthquake anticipates, or it already allows to run: not only the United States, but throughout the West, and it may not only be here.
In the United States as in Europe, the crisis seems to speed up the phenomenon that has been covered for some time, so that, in the new climate, they are solidifying and revealing.
The first of these phenomena is the updating, the extraordinary revival, of the dual sovereign state category, in relation to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis is indeed a crisis of banking-financial institutions which, of course, have close relations with abroad, but which, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of people and families living in one country, in one state.
This immediately creates a political problem for who governs it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically, it is almost only here nationally.
Political internationalization seems really out of play or has little to say: the clear evidence is provided by the European Union which, shared as usual, between various interests and between the various national strategies, cannot decide any common political lines.
And so it is from the government of each State that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all credit: when we go through a difficult period, there are only those States that have economic resources, the mass of financial resources capable of trying to put things back in place.
They also have the necessary means and legitimacy to use them: two resources of invaluable value, elements that no market or international organization can ever have in a similar way.
This new emphasis of the state-nation crisis is still in perfect harmony with the increasing importance that the most recent economic developments in the economy tend to attribute to a rather related factor: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we were now entering the realm of the network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, of non-materials, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized once and for all that our future would have to settle its accounts more and more with the rather little material things like water, crops, oil.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another from the earth, but which are absolutely linked to a confined space, to a territory.
So, who is sovereign, certainly has more cards than he who is not, that is, the one who has the evil of living in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
Now I come to the second novelty, which nevertheless provides for a fracture.
He who says Territoire, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and hence Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who knows how to take the situation in hand.
On the other hand, a discretionary wave for existing leaderships, economic species that have proved to be inadequate and full of shadow.
And also, something even deeper, in a certain sense, even worrying: a discredit, suffering, an image of inadequacy, a feeling of remoteness that tends to involve the entire class of directors in an increasing number of Western countries.
Thus, it further increases the conviction of the various classes, before actions are the same ideas of the social elites so far to their support, how to listen and be, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have the same time, and to be increasingly alien to the opinions of the majority.
in short, The demand for leadership, subterraneanly nourishes, a powerful and ramified movement of delegitimates of the ruling classes and traditional political orders, which manifest themselves in the improvised electoral "revolts" or, in the changes of collective moods of the latter all the time, from the conservative rise in Austria Bavaria, to the fall of workers in Great Britain, to the rebellion of American congressmen against Bush (and it may well be that the victory of the right in Italy did not come by chance).
