Adieu old cinema Paradiso, the cities provide the historic halls.
Historical cinemas close to multiplexes.
"A city without cinema halls is a blind town, it's like a face without eyes"
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what is happening in the great Italian urban centres, but also in the cities of the province,
The process of marginalizing the cinemas, with the birth on the periphery of the great multisales, and the death of consumption of the mono-rooms in the central areas of the cities, is one of the major events that seems to us to be inescapable and undisputable; in addition, it has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear, these are often historic places that are charged with memory, "it's as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a piece of road and so many emotions" observes the director of the New Cinema Paradiso, a film that offers to Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar and the Grand Prix of the jury of Cannes, and who told the poetry of a province hall, and the nostalgia of a way to live the cinema, lost can be forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the leading trader's association, mean everything: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and these are the rooms of the main cities that have paid the most: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the areas most affected by the closure, Emilie Romaine is headed by 82 lost mono cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The evidence confirms that the first person responsible for their disappearance is the advent of multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-story cinemas: 195 screens in Lombardy over the past five years, 81 in Tuscany as well as in Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exploitation has developed in an irrational way" observes Paolo Protti, President of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it is also necessary to guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a firm room in a city, these visitors are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplex.
Without talking about the lack of credit for traders: the previous debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not comply with existing laws.
In order to support the sector, between €16 million and €18 million are needed per year.
We note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, concerned about these closures, decided to resolve the situation through the signing of a protocol between Mairie and Anec, the first such in Italy, to defend and promote the mono cinemas of historical and periphery centers.
Among the proposed regulations, there are tax facilities for managers and benefits to the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area, and will have special rates for parking and in some parking spaces.
"It's an initiative that pleases" observes Giuseppe Tornatore "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna putting in place other measures.
However, it is clear that, in contrast to the super power of multiplexes, traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, as today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema in Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Cinema Paradiso" to which I had been thinking for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass before the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have had so many shared emotions, I turn from the other side to not see the black panels through the dust.
